lMHzRHTRr8KsBLThBxioVPT13B7Un5n0JyoNcDWjk2qEnV_M0OCmbqELB-GmqeVKHPi0f3fQAFR1tK8TKr2C0ipzOrjqpN4TFaF7ZAQ-z0Su2sVcSGCPGPqZhiTHw-J0JPq8Y08k5od8YlKVAb-U1lA3LH1059y_mNxs67KnlZPCF_Wt_dBfTIilUqVVvYJJfAO8aYlhMitJOt5qPcHDCopZ-RI8ooWIkirEBfWj-IbFwBS_tX9p6e_epSA7CpsoOVMA-ljB5cqUsE-Eyxc0skC09kTTKiCq8qTLRUddFY0PKx2wZSxSGwNfC9MqlDOFNtthSo3FXMun_xkAJDpa-2ir1a9SoFVY-eIX-qqfGppFWivKxFVAjOMa3\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dynamic class loading**\\n\\nI'm dealing with an issue about missing throws related to NoClassDef. It could be that native support is lacking or that ordinary reflection isn't sufficient. If a method fundamentally relies on dynamic class loading, I might need to catch an error and verify unsupported statuses. The rule mentions using `Class.forName` only if the classes are in metadata and potentially using method handles for resolution.\\n\\nI need a concise approach, maybe by adding tests like `compilerGeneratedClassResolverUsesClassForNameViaMethodHandle` to report missing functionality. There’s an existing helper that I might consider removing since it’s unused, but it hasn't caused any harm. I'll strive to keep things minimal.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating helper usage**\\n\\nI’m looking at the base64 helper method, which is currently active but has no associated tests. I’m wondering if I should revert to a prior version or if that’s unnecessary. It seems unused, so maybe I could generate a direct helper like before, but it looks like the file update is the only change I’m considering. However, I don’t think it’s crucial to make any adjustments right now. It might be better to leave things as they are.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Editing content type**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to finalize everything, especially with the content type. I need to edit some specifics — like whether to use the MethodHandles import before or after the package declaration. I also need to remember that existing style prefers imports from Java before Groovy or library imports. The AGENTS approach indicates I should include imports and type annotations. Okay, I’ll need to ensure I consider the top-level public aspect as well.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing closure handling**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to implement the `CLOSURE_CLASS_NAME` for the `ResponseSpecificationImpl`. The test needs to verify that the `compilerGeneratedClassResolver` correctly uses `forName` with the class name. The potential issues with `LinkageError` and `UnsupportedNativeImageError` also come up. I’ll need to create a helper method for resolving the class. \\n\\nImporting `io.restassured.internal.ResponseSpecificationImpl` might be necessary, and I wonder about the Native Groovy initialization. Is it really needed for `method handle class$`? It could be that `findClass` for the closure class may trigger the initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering initialization issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how `findClass` might not load and initialize correctly. The `privateLookupIn` could also possibly fail because of how it links to the super groovy Closure. So, I should be ready to catch `LinkageError`. \\n\\nThe method `rethrowUnlessUnsupportedNativeImageError` seems related to `NativeImageSupport`, and I need to be aware of that available import. If there’s an `UnsupportedFeatureError`, my exception handling will swallow the issue, but that would still allow the test to pass if native doesn’t support the dynamic `Class.forName`. Existing patterns should hold up, so that’s reassuring.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_e8bSxwkzsp875oVaDRiQjtaZ|fc_0fae711bda365903016a01652475a081949f568550cfcb6a48", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/ResponseSpecificationImplInner_contentType_closure12Test.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "package io_rest_assured.rest_assure